The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 The gold tikli that had been missing from the forehead of an idol at Sree Sree Sitalnath Swamiji Temple, at Maniktala, since Tuesday was found on Friday morning. Police said the ornament, fitted with a two-carat diamond, was found on a platter at the base of the idol. It was noticed by devotees who informed the police. The detective department had detained two employees of the temple. The tikli had been on the deitys forehead since the 70s.

 Calcutta High Court on Friday asked the state government 

 to file a fresh petition seeking revival of the guidelines 

 for road-encroaching pandals. The state on Thursday urged 

 the court to revive the guidelines. 

 The order for a fresh petition was issued by the division 

 bench of Chief Justice V.S. Sirpurkar and Justice Nadira 

 Patherya. Advocate-general Balai Ray said the government 

 would move the fresh petition in a couple of days. 

 Fire services minister Pratim Chatterjee on Friday asked 

 Puja organisers across the city to strictly abide by fire-safety 

 norms. At a meeting with the organisers, the minister issued 

 a series of guidelines, including one on the use of fire-resistant 

 material. Use of inflammable material like matchsticks, 

 tyres and bamboo leaves should be avoided, he added. 

 Information and technology minister Debesh Das on Friday inaugurated the Calcutta centre of the Bangkok-based Digital Asia School of Animation (DASA), in the presence of the Thai consul-general Manop Mekprayoonthong and CPM parliamentarian Lakshman Seth. DASA has tied up with a city-based education consultant, Overseas Consultant, to run the institution. The centre, with 35 seats, will provide one-year training on film animation and games development. The session starts next month.

 British Airways on Friday announced an extension of its special fares to the UK and other destinations from Calcutta and other parts of India, by another five weeks. The return fare for London from Calcutta is Rs 20,000 (taxes applicable) and for the US from Calcutta is Rs 33,000 (taxes applicable). To avail of the special fare, passengers must book tickets before September 30. The deadline for outbound travel is February 28, 2007.

 Amanullah Khan, 35, secretary of Amar Moni Primary School in Khardah, on the northern fringes of the city, was shot dead on Friday morning. Police said Khan was going home after attending a meeting in the school. No one has been arrested 

 Prabhat Sapui, 32, was arrested in Sonarpur, on the southern fringes of the city, on Friday on charges of cheating. Police said he had taken around Rs 4 lakh from several persons after promising them jobs. The arrest followed complaints by some of the victims.

 Saharunnisa Biwi, 55, a resident of Russell Street, was critically injured after being knocked down by a vehicle near Babughat on Friday morning. The woman was taken to SSKM Hospital, where she died. 

 Aakaash Agrawal, 28, was found hanging in a room in Ambassador Guest House on Rajamohan Street, under Jorasanko police station, on Friday morning. Police said Agarwal was a resident of Orissa. No suicide note was found. 

 Nidhiram Mondal, 60, fell unconscious in a private bus near the Maidan on Friday morning. He was taken to SSKM Hospital, where he was pronounced dead. Mondal was a resident of Lakshmikantapur, South 24-Parganas.

